  title = {Mythos and Tyrannos},
  comment = {vita-4 Greek for Myth and Tyrants. As of the 5th century B.C.E.
             *mythos* came to mean 'an entertaining if not necessarily
             trustworthy tale.' While *tyrannos*was a form of monarchy, not a
             necessarily bad or unpopular one, that was set up by Greek usurpers
             in the 7th and 6th centuries B.C.E. The pair taken together could
             refer to: the myth of tyrants and how they interacted with their
             world and ours through history; the intersection of myth and belief
             in Ancient Greece and its influence on the tyrants of the age; or
             how tyrants used myth and religion in order to help in their
